\section{Behaviour  of special fields in Kerr space-time}
Teukolsky managed to decouple and separate Maxwell equations on type D background for the scalars $\phi_0$ and $\phi_2$~\cite{teuk1} of a general electromagnetic field in the form (\ref{phiab}). A decoupled equation can also be found for $\phi_1$, though it can not be separated in Kerr geometry. Teukolsky's parametrised  master equation is satisfied by $\phi_0$ for $s=1$, and by $\rho^{-2} \phi_2$ for $s=-1$. Considering the asymptotic solutions as $r \to \infty$, it turns out that $\phi_2$ is dominant for the outgoing waves at infinity, and $\phi_0$ is dominant for ingoing waves at infinity. The solutions are given by 
\begin{eqnarray}
&& \phi_2 \sim\rme^{ \rmi \omega r*}/r  \mbox{ outgoing waves} \nonumber \\
&&  \phi_0 \sim \rme^{- \rmi \omega r*}/r  \mbox{ ingoing waves} \label{solninfty}
\end{eqnarray}
where $r^*$ is the tortoise coordinate defined by $dr^*/dr=(r^2+a^2)/\Delta$. (Here $\Delta=r^2 - 2Mr + a^2$ not to be confused with NP derivative operator $\Delta$.) Note that $r^* \to r$ as $r \to \infty$.

