& &l^\mu=[(r^2 + a^2)/\Delta ,1,0,a/\Delta],\quad n^\mu=[(r^2+a^2, -\Delta ,0,a]/(2\Sigma) \nonumber \\
& &m^\mu=[ia \sin \theta ,0,1, i/\sin \theta]/[\sqrt{2}(r+ia \cos \theta)]
\label{tetrad0}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\Sigma=r^2+a^2\cos^2\theta$ and $\Delta$ was defined after equation (\ref{solninfty}). Using  this tetrad we see that the expression $[l_{(1}n_{0)}+ m_{(1}m_{0)}^*]=[l_{(1}n_{3)}+ m_{(1}m_{3)}^*]=0$. This implies that $T^1_{\;\; 0}$  and $T^1_{\;\; 3}$ vanish everywhere if $\phi_1$ is the only non-vanishing Maxwell scalar for an electromagnetic field in Kerr space-time, regardless of the solution for the field.  Thus, the contribution of the special  electromagnetic field introduced in section (\ref{sec}) to the radial energy and angular momentum fluxes  vanishes everywhere, in Kerr background. In other words reflection or transmission of these waves do not lead to any perturbation of black hole parameters of mass and angular momentum.

Let us evaluate the behaviour of null fields in Kerr background. The nonvanishing spin coefficients are 
\begin{eqnarray}
&&\rho= -1/(r-\rm{i}a\cos \theta,\quad \beta=-\rho^* \cot \theta /2\sqrt{2}, \quad \pi=\rm{i}a\rho^2 \sin \theta /\sqrt{2} \nonumber \\
&& \tau= \rm{i} a \rho \rho^* \sin \theta /\sqrt{2}, \quad \mu=\rho^2 \rho^* \Delta/2 ,\quad \gamma= \mu +  \rho \rho^* (r-M)/2, \nonumber \\ &&\alpha=\pi-\beta^* \label{coeffskerr}
\end{eqnarray}
For the null field which lies along $l^a$, (using $D\rho=\rho^2$) the solution for $(D-\rho)\phi_2=0$ is

nexttext:
The expression (\ref{deltatwo}) is negative definite. Thus, if we start with an extremal black hole, the null field along $l^a$ --acting alone-- turns it into a naked singularity, and CCC is violated. The fact that  $\delta {\mathcal{C}}$ is always negative implies that the initial data giving rise to violation is not confined to a set of measure zero. In this sense the violation of CCC by null fields along $l^a$ is generic~(see \cite{waldrev}).

The generic violation of CCC by null fields along $l^a$  may seem to contradict the result of our previous work~\cite{emccc} that CCC is preserved in the interaction of electromagnetic fields with an extremal Kerr black hole. In fact, the solution for test electromagnetic fields in Kerr background by Teukolsky and Press which was used in that work, does not cover null fields so the results of the two works are independent. To see this consider the solutions of Teukolsky and Press at infinity~\cite{teuk1,teuk3}
\begin{eqnarray}
\phi_2 &\sim & e^{-i\omega t }e^{im\phi}({}_{-1}S_{lm})(Z_{\rm{in}} e^{-i\omega r*}/r^3 + Z_{\rm{out}} e^{i\omega r*}/r)\nonumber \\
\phi_0 &\sim &  e^{-i\omega t }e^{im\phi}({}_{1}S_{lm})(Y_{\rm{in}} e^{-i\omega r*}/r + Y_{\rm{out}} e^{i\omega r*}/r^3)\nonumber \\
& &
\label{solution0}
\end{eqnarray}
The amplitudes are related to each other by 
\begin{eqnarray}
&&-2\omega^2 Y_{\rm{out}}=BZ_{\rm{out}} \label{yout} \\
&&B Y_{\rm{in}}=-8\omega^2Z_{\rm{in}} \label{yin}
\end{eqnarray}
where $B$ is a positive constant (see~\cite{teuk3}). If we let $\phi_2=0$ in (\ref{solution0}), then by (\ref{yout}) and (\ref{yin})  $\phi_0$ becomes  zero, and vice versa. Therefore the null solutions $(\phi_0=\phi_1=0 ; \quad\phi_2=\phi)$ and $(\phi_2=\phi_1=0; \quad \phi_0=\phi)$ are not included in the results of Teukolsky and Press.

The validity of CCC in the case of the special non-null field is trivial. For this field we have $T^{1}_{\;\;0}=T^{1}_{\;\;3}=0 \Rightarrow \delta {\mathcal{C}} =0$. The non-null field   does not lead to any perturbation of black hole parameters of mass and angular momentum, hence does not challenge CCC whether we start with an extremal or a nearly extremal black hole.
\section{Summary and conclusions}
In this paper, after a brief review of electromagnetism and gravity in Newman Penrose formalism, we  proved that every space-time of Petrov type D admits a special test electromagnetic field such that the principal null directions of the electromagnetic field coincide with those of the space-time. This corresponds to a solution of Maxwell equations such that the only non-vanishing Maxwell scalar is $\phi_1$, given in (\ref{maxspecial}). Bianchi identities in vacuum for a type D space-time (all the scalars of the Weyl tensor except $\Psi_2$ vanish) are given in (\ref{bianchispe}). Manifestly, the integrability conditions for these two systems are identical. In other words, the integrability conditions for the existence of the relevant electromagnetic field in a type D space-time are identical with the conditions of the existence of the type D space-time itself. We also explicitly evaluated the integrability conditions for both cases together, to clarify  their equivalence. Next we stated that the solution for this electromagnetic field has the form $\phi_1=\rho^2 C_1$, so it behaves as $1/r^2$ everywhere, in every space-time of type D, including Kerr space-time. Due to $1/r^2$ behaviour the contribution of this electromagnetic field to energy and angular momentum fluxes at infinity vanishes. In fact, the form of the energy momentum tensor (\ref{tmunu}) suggests that the contribution to energy and angular momentum fluxes vanishes everywhere in Kerr background, if $\phi_1$ is the only non-vanishing Maxwell scalar for the electromagnetic field, regardless of the solution for the field. Thus, the special electromagnetic field introduced in section (\ref{sec}) does not lead to any perturbation of the mass and angular momentum of Kerr black holes. Also two null electromagnetic fields simultaneously and independently exist in Petrov type D space-times. These fields are directed along the repeated principal null directions $l^a$ and $n^a$, and the only non-vanishing Maxwell scalars are $\phi_2$ and $\phi_0$, respectively. These fields behave as $1/r$ at infinity and satisfy the limit condition (\ref{limit}) so that the contribution to fluxes of energy and angular momentum can be calculated. 

Considering the interaction of Kerr black holes with the null field along $n^a$, the cosmic censorship conjecture of Penrose remains valid whether we start with an extremal or a nearly extremal black hole. The special non-null field can not challenge CCC either since it does not lead to any perturbation of the mass and angular momentum of Kerr black holes. However, the null field along $l^a$ leads to a generic violation of CCC. In each case we derived the results simply by direct substitution from the NP tetrad (\ref{tetrad0}) to the energy-momentum tensor (\ref{tmunu}). Elementary algebra yields that the cosmic censorship criterion $\delta {\mathcal{C}}$ is always positive/negative if the only non-vanishing Maxwell scalar for the electromagnetic field is $\phi_0$/$\phi_2$. The fact that $\delta {\mathcal{C}}$ is always negative implies that the violation of CCC due to null electromagnetic fields along $l^a$ is generic,
  since  the initial data giving rise to violation is not confined to a set of measure zero.
